      "message": "If I\u0027ve got this right, 0x8c0 is 2240 bytes, 140 16-byte records.  So I think we\u0027re undercounting the size change here... we\u0027re not counting the size of the string names themselves which I guess don\u0027t have symbol names and won\u0027t show up in nm, but should show up if you run `size`:\n\n$ size out/obj/src/utils/libskia.SkParseColor.o\n   text\t   data\t    bss\t    dec\t    hex\tfilename\n   3113\t      0\t      0\t   3113\t    c29\tout/obj/src/utils/libskia.SkParseColor.o\n\n~~~\u003e\n\n   text\t   data\t    bss\t    dec\t    hex\tfilename\n   2970\t   2240\t      0\t   5210\t   145a\tout/obj/src/utils/libskia.SkParseColor.o\n\nSo I think we\u0027re +2K here.  If that\u0027s okay with you, I think we\u0027re good to go.\n\nThere\u0027s some low hanging fruit here, like storing alpha\u003d0xff redundantly, or the 4-byte dead space after fColor.  That\u0027d get you 700 bytes back I think:\n\n    #pragma pack(push,1)\n    struct ColorRec {\n        const char* name;\n        uint8_t bgr[3];\n    };\n    #pragma pack(pop)\n\nIf the size _really_ matters, and this list doesn\u0027t change often (ever), I don\u0027t think the spirit of the old encoding was really a bad idea, but I guess it wasn\u0027t resilient to the fuzzer?  Makes me want to try things like a perfect hash table or some sort of dense trie, where we spend a bunch of effort offline to make it small and fast.",
